Inexact-ADMM Based Federated Meta-Learning for Fast and Continual Edge Learning

Sheng Yue Central South University Arizona State University sheng.yue@csu.edu.cn ,¬† Ju Ren Central South University renju@csu.edu.cn ,¬† Jiang Xin Central South University xinjiang@csu.edu.cn ,¬† Sen Lin Arizona State University sen.lin.1@asu.edu ¬†and¬† Junshan Zhang Arizona State University junshan.zhang@asu.edu
(2021)
Abstract.

In order to meet the requirements for performance, safety, and latency in many IoT applications, intelligent decisions must be made right here right now at the network edge. However, the constrained resources and limited local data amount pose significant challenges to the development of edge AI. To overcome these challenges, we explore continual edge learning capable of leveraging the knowledge transfer from previous tasks. Aiming to achieve fast and continual edge learning, we propose a platform-aided federated meta-learning architecture where edge nodes collaboratively learn a meta-model, aided by the knowledge transfer from prior tasks. The edge learning problem is cast as a regularized optimization problem, where the valuable knowledge learned from previous tasks is extracted as regularization. Then, we devise an ADMM based federated meta-learning algorithm, namely ADMM-FedMeta, where ADMM offers a natural mechanism to decompose the original problem into many subproblems which can be solved in parallel across edge nodes and the platform. Further, a variant of inexact-ADMM method is employed where the subproblems are ‚Äòsolved‚Äô via linear approximation as well as Hessian estimation to reduce the computational cost per round to ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n). We provide a comprehensive analysis of ADMM-FedMeta, in terms of the convergence properties, the rapid adaptation performance, and the forgetting effect of prior knowledge transfer, for the general non-convex case. Extensive experimental studies demonstrate the effectiveness and efficiency of ADMM-FedMeta and showcase that it substantially outperforms the existing baselines.

edge intelligence, continual learning, federated meta-learning, regularization, ADMM

1. Introduction

The past few years have witnessed an explosive growth of Internet of Things (IoT) devices. In many of these IoT applications, decisions must be made in real time to meet the requirements for safety, accuracy, and performance (Zhang et¬†al., 2020b). A general consensus is that the conventional cloud-based approach would not work well in these applications, calling for edge intelligence or edge AI (Zhou et¬†al., 2019; Park et¬†al., 2019). Built on a synergy of edge computing and AI, edge intelligence is expected to push the frontier of model training and inference processes to the network edge in the physical proximity of IoT devices and data sources. Nevertheless, it is highly nontrivial for a single edge node to achieve real-time edge intelligence since AI model training usually requires extensive computing resources and a large number of data samples. To tackle these challenges, we resort to continual learning capable of leveraging the knowledge transfer from previous tasks in the cloud or by other edge nodes. Simply put, continual learning (CL) is a machine learning paradigm that is designed to sequentially learn from data samples corresponding to different tasks (Parisi et¬†al., 2019). Rather than learning the new model from scratch, CL aims to design algorithms leveraging knowledge transfer from pre-trained models to the new learning task, assuming that the training data of previous tasks are unavailable for the newly coming task (this is the case for edge learning).

To facilitate edge learning, collaborative learning has recently been proposed to leverage the model knowledge distillation, including cloud-edge collaboration and edge-edge collaboration. More specifically, a distributionally robust optimization based edge learning framework has been introduced to build a cloud-edge synergy between the pre-trained model in the cloud and the local data samples at the edge (Zhang et¬†al., 2020b). Along a different avenue, building on the recent advances in meta-learning (Finn et¬†al., 2017; Nichol et¬†al., 2018) and federated learning (McMahan et¬†al., 2017), a significant body of work has been devoted to federated meta-learning (Jiang et¬†al., 2019a; Chen et¬†al., 2018; Zheng et¬†al., 2020; Lin et¬†al., 2020) and personalized federated learning (Fallah et¬†al., 2020b; Wu et¬†al., 2020), under a common theme of fostering edge-edge collaboration. In particular, federated meta-learning aims to learn a good model initialization (meta-model) across source edge nodes, such that the model of the new task can be learned via fast adaptation from the meta-initialization with only a few data samples at the target edge node.

Most of the existing works on federated meta-learning focus on the learning from a given set of tasks, each with its training data, but have not addressed the well-known catastrophic forgetting issue in continual learning (French, 1999) (Parisi et¬†al., 2019). Further, the performance of the fast adaptation depends on the similarity among tasks (Lin et¬†al., 2020; Fallah et¬†al., 2020b). As a result, the meta-model obtained via federated meta-learning may not work well when the tasks on the target node are dissimilar to those at the source nodes. It is also worth noting that most of the existing federated meta-learning algorithms are gradient-based, which may suffer from some limitations such as vanishing gradients and sensitivity to poor conditioning (Wang et¬†al., 2019b). It has been observed in practice that these gradient-based algorithms often exhibit slow convergence in training the meta-model, especially on complex tasks (Fallah et¬†al., 2020b; Jiang et¬†al., 2019a; Chen et¬†al., 2018), resulting in low communication efficiency and high computational cost.

To tackle the issues noted above, in this paper, we study continual edge learning via federated meta-learning with regularization. Notably, regularization-based methods have been widely used in continual learning (Kirkpatrick et¬†al., 2017; Zenke et¬†al., 2017; Schwarz et¬†al., 2018) and transfer learning (Takada and Fujisawa, 2020; Si et¬†al., 2009). Inspired by theoretical neuroscience models via imposing constraints on the update of the neural weights (Barros et¬†al., 2018), regularization approaches can help to alleviate catastrophic forgetting (Parisi et¬†al., 2019). Meanwhile, valuable knowledge learned from previous tasks can be extracted as regularization to improve the training speed and the performance of the new task (so-called ‚Äúpositive forward transfer‚Äù (Lopez-Paz and Ranzato, 2017)). Accordingly, we cast the federated meta-learning problem as a regularized stochastic optimization problem, using Bregman divergence (Bregman, 1967) to define the regularization. Further, to reduce the computational cost and to facilitate collaborative learning, we employ the alternative direction method of multipliers (ADMM) technique to decompose the problem into a set of subproblems that can be solved in parallel across edge nodes and the platform. In particular, by ‚Äúdecoupling the regularizer‚Äù from the computation at local edge nodes, it suffices to run the regularization only in the platform for global aggregation. Observe that the conventional ADMM technique requires the exact solutions to a set of (possibly non-convex) subproblems during each iteration, incurring a possibly high computational cost. To overcome this challenge, we develop a variant of the inexact-ADMM algorithm for the regularized federated meta-learning problem, namely ADMM-FedMeta, where we use linear approximation in each subproblem111As shown in the proof of convergence of ADMM-FedMeta, it is unnecessary to obtain the exact solutions in each iteration, and this is the underlying rationale of the inexact-ADMM., as well as Hessian estimation, and then transform it into a quadratic form that can be solved with a closed-form solution, thus achieving computational complexity of ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n) per round, with nùëõn being the model dimension.

We note that the error induced by linear approximation and Hessian estimation, complicates the proof of the convergence of the proposed algorithm, and the existing results (Wang et¬†al., 2019a; Barber and Sidky, 2020; Hong et¬†al., 2016) cannot be applied directly, simply because the sufficient descent condition of the Lagrangian function is violated. In this paper, we develop a new technical path to resolve this issue and establish the convergence guarantee for the general non-convex case. Further, we rigorously show that our method can mitigate the catastrophic forgetting and alleviate the performance degradation due to the dissimilarity between the source nodes and the target node. Besides, different from the previous approaches (Lin et¬†al., 2020; Fallah et¬†al., 2020b), our algorithm can converge under mild conditions, i.e., without regular similarity assumptions on the training nodes. Therefore, it can be applied to unbalanced and heterogeneous local datasets, unleashing the potential in dealing with the inherent challenges in federated learning.

The main contributions of this work are summarized as follows:

  • ‚Ä¢

    Aiming to facilitate fast and continual edge learning, we propose a platform-aided federated-meta learning architecture where edge nodes join forces to learn a meta-model with the knowledge transfer from previous tasks. We cast the edge learning problem as a regularized optimization problem, in which the transferred knowledge is in the form of regularization using Bregman divergence. We devise an inexact-ADMM based algorithm, called ADMM-FedMeta, where the ADMM technique is employed to decompose the problem into a set of subproblems that can be solved in parallel across edge nodes and the platform, and also it suffices to run the regularization only in the platform for global aggregation. Further, a variant of the inexact-ADMM method is devised where the subproblems are ‚Äòsolved‚Äô via linear approximation as well as Hessian estimation to reduce the computational cost of per round to ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n), achieving lower computational complexity compared to most of the existing methods.

  • ‚Ä¢

    We carry out a comprehensive analysis of the proposed algorithm for the general non-convex case, where we establish the convergence and characterize the performance of fast adaptation using local samples at the target node. We also quantify the forgetting effect of model knowledge transferred from previous tasks for a special case. Besides, we show that ADMM-FedMeta can mitigate performance degradation incurred by the dissimilarity between the source nodes and the target node.

  • ‚Ä¢

    We evaluate the performance of the proposed algorithm on different models and benchmark datasets. Our extensive experimental results showcase that ADMM-FedMeta outperforms existing state-of-the-art approaches, in terms of convergence speed, adaptation performance, and the capability of learning without forgetting, especially with small sample sizes.

2. Related work

In this section, we briefly review the related work in the following three areas.

Meta-Learning. Meta-learning has emerged as a promising solution for few-shot learning. Ravi et al. (Ravi and Larochelle, 2016) propose an LSTM-based meta-learning model to learn an optimization algorithm for training neural networks. Different from (Ravi and Larochelle, 2016), a gradient-based Model Agnostic Meta-Learning (MAML) algorithm is proposed in (Finn et¬†al., 2017), which aims at learning a model initialization, based on which using a few gradient descent updates can achieve satisfactory performance on a new task. To reduce the computational complexity, Nichol et al. (Nichol et¬†al., 2018) introduce a first-order meta-learning algorithm called Reptile, which does not require the computation of the second-order derivatives. Multiple follow-up works extend MAML from different perspectives, e.g., (Raghu et¬†al., 2019; Collins et¬†al., 2020; Song et¬†al., 2019; Finn et¬†al., 2018). Along a different line, Fallah et al. (Fallah et¬†al., 2020a) establish the convergence of one-step MAML for non-convex loss functions and then proposes a Hessian-free MAML to reduce the computational cost with theoretical guarantees. The convergence for multi-step MAML is studied in (Ji et¬†al., 2020). Wang et al. (Wang et¬†al., 2020) further characterize the gap between the stationary point and the global optimum of MAML in a general non-convex setting.

Federated Meta-Learning. Very recently, the integration of federated learning and MAML has garnered much attention. Chen et al. (Chen et¬†al., 2018) propose a federated meta-learning framework called FedMeta based on FedAvg (McMahan et¬†al., 2017) and MAML-type algorithms, which improves the performance and convergence speed of FedAvg. Jiang et al. (Jiang et¬†al., 2019a) analyze the connections between FedAvg and MAML, and proposes a federated meta-learning algorithm called personalized FedAvg. Lin et al. (Lin et¬†al., 2020) analyze the convergence properties and computational complexity of federated meta-learning for a strongly convex setting. Another recent work (Fallah et¬†al., 2020b) proposes a federated meta-learning algorithm called Per-FedAvg and provides the convergence guarantee for the general non-convex setting. However, these studies focus on collaborative learning on a given set of tasks without exploring the valuable knowledge transfer from the previous tasks (Parisi et¬†al., 2019).

ADMM. A number of existing works (Wang et¬†al., 2014; Hong et¬†al., 2016; Magn√∫sson et¬†al., 2015; Wang et¬†al., 2019a) analyze the convergence of ADMM for the case where the solution to each subproblem is computed exactly. Wang et al. (Wang et¬†al., 2018) extend the ADMM method from two-block to multi-block form. Besides, there are also a few works (Mukkamala et¬†al., 2020; Jiang et¬†al., 2019b; Lanza et¬†al., 2017; Barber and Sidky, 2020) studying the performance of ADMM in an inexact and non-convex setting, by linearizing the subproblems that are difficult to solve exactly. It is worth noting that linear approximation is insufficient for the meta-learning problem which generally requires higher-order information.

3. Continual Edge Learning via Federated Meta-Learning With Regularization

We consider a platform-aided federated meta-learning architecture for edge learning (as illustrated in Figure 1), where a set ‚Ñê‚Ñê\mathcal{I} of source edge nodes joint force to learn a meta-model, aided by the valuable knowledge learned from previous tasks in the cloud. Specifically, the knowledge transfer is in the form of regularization using Bregman divergence on the prior model.

Motivated by the recent success of regularization approaches in transfer learning and continual learning (Parisi et¬†al., 2019), we use regularization for extracting the valuable knowledge from the prior model to facilitate fast edge training and to alleviate catastrophic forgetting. More specially, for a model parameter Œ∏‚àà‚ÑùnùúÉsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, we denote Œ∏p‚àà‚ÑùnsubscriptùúÉùëùsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta_{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{n} as the prior model parameter, and use the Bregman divergence Dh‚Äã(Œ∏,Œ∏p)subscriptùê∑‚ÑéùúÉsubscriptùúÉùëùD_{h}(\theta,\theta_{p}) (Bregman, 1967) as the regularization, given by:

(1) Dh‚Äã(Œ∏,Œ∏p)‚âúh‚Äã(Œ∏)‚àíh‚Äã(Œ∏p)‚àí‚ü®‚àáh‚Äã(Œ∏p),Œ∏‚àíŒ∏p‚ü©,‚âúsubscriptùê∑‚ÑéùúÉsubscriptùúÉùëù‚ÑéùúÉ‚ÑésubscriptùúÉùëù‚àá‚ÑésubscriptùúÉùëùùúÉsubscriptùúÉùëù\displaystyle D_{h}(\theta,\theta_{p})\triangleq h(\theta)-h(\theta_{p})-\langle\nabla h\big{(}\theta_{p}\big{)},\theta-\theta_{p}\rangle,

for some continuously-differentiable strictly convex function h‚Äã(‚ãÖ)‚Ñé‚ãÖh(\cdot). It is worth noting that Bregman divergence is a dissimilarity measure between two objects (e.g., vectors, matrices, distributions, etc.). It encompasses a rich class of divergence metrics, including squared Euclidean distance, squared Mahalanobis distance, Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence, and Itakura-Saito (IS) distance, which are widely used in machine learning to encode the dissimilarity from different perspectives, and is particularly useful for the regularization approaches (Si et¬†al., 2009; Yu et¬†al., 2013; Jung et¬†al., 2016). Note that while for ease of exposition, in this paper we consider the regularizer on the model parameters using Bregman divergence, the same methodology can be applied to generalize the regularization to be in terms of Bregman divergence between two functions of Œ∏ùúÉ\theta and Œ∏psubscriptùúÉùëù\theta_{p}, respectively (see Assumption 2).

Following the same line as in MAML (Finn et¬†al., 2017), we divide the dataset ùíüisubscriptùíüùëñ\mathcal{D}_{i} for the source edge node i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I} into two disjoint sets, i.e., the support set ùíüissubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñ\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i} and the query set ùíüiqsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùëûùëñ\mathcal{D}^{q}_{i}. Based on the prior model, we can formulate the federated meta-learning with knowledge transfer among the source edge nodes as the following regularized optimization problem:

where wi‚âúDi/‚àëi‚àà‚ÑêDi‚âúsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùê∑ùëñsubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùê∑ùëñw_{i}\triangleq D_{i}/\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}D_{i}, Œ±ùõº\alpha is the learning rate, and ŒªùúÜ\lambda is a penalty parameter that can be used to balance the trade-off between the loss and the regularization. In this formulation, we aim to find a good meta-model such that slight updating, i.e., one-step gradient descent, results in substantial performance improvement for any task across the edge nodes. That is, the source edge nodes collaboratively learn how to learn fast with a few data samples. Further, by penalizing changes in the model via regularization, the learned model from (2)-(4) is confined to stay ‚Äòclose‚Äô to the prior model for enabling collaborative edge learning without forgetting prior knowledge, thus the learned meta-model can widely adapt to different types of tasks.

In the fast adaptation stage, the platform transfers the learned meta-model Œ∏ùúÉ\theta to the target node (denoted by mùëöm) after solving the regularized federated meta-learning problem (2)-(4). Based on Œ∏ùúÉ\theta, the target node mùëöm can use its local data set ùíümssubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëö\mathcal{D}^{s}_{m} to quickly compute a new model œïmsubscriptitalic-œïùëö\phi_{m} by performing one-step stochastic gradient descent, i.e.,

(5) œïm=Œ∏‚àíŒ±‚Äã‚àáLm‚Äã(Œ∏,ùíüms).subscriptitalic-œïùëöùúÉùõº‚àásubscriptùêøùëöùúÉsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëö\displaystyle\phi_{m}=\theta-\alpha\nabla L_{m}(\theta,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{m}).

Note that the target node also can execute a few steps of stochastic gradient descent updates for better performance when needed.

3.2. An Inexact-ADMM Based Algorithm for Regularized Federated Meta-Learning

As alluded to earlier, general gradient-based federated meta-learning approaches cannot handle the regularized optimization problem (2)-(4) well. To address this problem, we propose an inexact-ADMM based federated meta-learning algorithm (ADMM-FedMeta) to solve (2)-(4).

Observe that the federated meta-learning problem (2)-(4) is equivalent to the following constrained optimization problem:

(6) min{Œ∏i},Œ∏‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚ÄãLi‚Äã(œïi‚Äã(Œ∏i),ùíüiq)+Œª‚ÄãDh‚Äã(Œ∏,Œ∏p)s.t.Œ∏i‚àíŒ∏=0,i‚àà‚ÑêsubscriptsubscriptùúÉùëñùúÉsubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùêøùëñsubscriptitalic-œïùëñsubscriptùúÉùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùëûùëñùúÜsubscriptùê∑‚ÑéùúÉsubscriptùúÉùëùs.t.formulae-sequencesubscriptùúÉùëñùúÉ0ùëñ‚Ñêmissing-subexpression\displaystyle\begin{split}\min_{\{\theta_{i}\},\theta}&\quad\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}L_{i}\big{(}\phi_{i}(\theta_{i}),\mathcal{D}^{q}_{i}\big{)}+\lambda D_{h}(\theta,\theta_{p})\\ \text{s.t.}\,&\quad\begin{array}[]{lr}\theta_{i}-\theta=0,~{}i\in\mathcal{I}\\ \end{array}\end{split}

where œïi‚Äã(Œ∏i)subscriptitalic-œïùëñsubscriptùúÉùëñ\phi_{i}(\theta_{i}) is given by (4). To solve (6), we form the augmented Lagrangian function as follows:

(7) +œÅi2‚à•Œ∏i‚àíŒ∏‚à•2)+ŒªDh(Œ∏,Œ∏p),\displaystyle+\frac{\rho_{i}}{2}\|\theta_{i}-\theta\|^{2}\Big{)}+\lambda D_{h}(\theta,\theta_{p}),

where yi‚àà‚Ñùnsubscriptùë¶ùëñsuperscript‚Ñùùëõy_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{n} is a dual variable and œÅi>0subscriptùúåùëñ0\rho_{i}>0 is a penalty parameter for each i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I}.

When the classical ADMM method is applied (Boyd et¬†al., 2011), the variables Œ∏isubscriptùúÉùëñ\theta_{i}, Œ∏ùúÉ\theta and yisubscriptùë¶ùëñy_{i} are updated alternatively in solving (6) as follows:

The conventional ADMM decomposes the problem (6) into a set of subproblems that can be solved in parallel, while computing Dh‚Äã(Œ∏,Œ∏p)subscriptùê∑‚ÑéùúÉsubscriptùúÉùëùD_{h}(\theta,\theta_{p}) and Li‚Äã(œïi‚Äã(Œ∏i),ùíüiq)subscriptùêøùëñsubscriptitalic-œïùëñsubscriptùúÉùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùëûùëñL_{i}\big{(}\phi_{i}(\theta_{i}),\mathcal{D}^{q}_{i}\big{)} separately. Based on that, to fully take advantage of the combined computation power of the local edge nodes and the platform, we provide the following alternating updating strategy: 1) updating Œ∏ùúÉ\theta at the platform and 2) updating {Œ∏i,yi}subscriptùúÉùëñsubscriptùë¶ùëñ\{\theta_{i},y_{i}\} at the source edge nodes in a distributed manner. Particularly, in this way, the computation corresponding to the regularizer can be decoupled from the edge nodes to the the platform. However, attaining the exact solution to each subproblem is computationally costly, especially with a complex DNN model. To tackle this challenge, we devise the inexact-ADMM based federated meta-learning (ADMM-FedMeta) below.

Specifically, in communication round t=0ùë°0t=0, the platform initializes Œ∏0superscriptùúÉ0\theta^{0} and sends it to all edge nodes. Each node i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I} initializes yi‚àí1subscriptsuperscriptùë¶1ùëñy^{-1}_{i} locally.

    Fast Adaptation. After the training phase, the platform transfers the learned meta-model Œ∏TsuperscriptùúÉùëá\theta^{T} to the target node mùëöm. Based on Œ∏TsuperscriptùúÉùëá\theta^{T}, the target node performs one or a few steps of stochastic gradient descent on its own dataset to obtain a new model.

The details of ADMM-FedMeta are summarized in Algorithm 1. Note that due to linearizing all decomposed subproblems and estimating Hessian by its first-order estimation, we enable the computation complexity of ADMM-FedMeta to be ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n) per round, which maintains the lowest among all existing federated meta-learning approaches.

4. Performance Analysis

In this section, we analyze the performance of ADMM-FedMeta. First, we study the convergence properties and characterize the communication complexity for ADMM-FedMeta. Then, we quantify the forgetting effect to previous tasks of the meta-model and analyze the fast adaptation performance at the target edge node.

4.1. Convergence Analysis

For convenience, we denote the objective function of (2) as F‚Äã(Œ∏)ùêπùúÉF(\theta):

(16) F‚Äã(Œ∏)‚âú‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚ÄãLi‚Äã(œïi‚Äã(Œ∏),ùíüiq)+Œª‚ÄãDh‚Äã(Œ∏,Œ∏p),‚âúùêπùúÉsubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùêøùëñsubscriptitalic-œïùëñùúÉsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùëûùëñùúÜsubscriptùê∑‚ÑéùúÉsubscriptùúÉùëù\displaystyle F(\theta)\triangleq\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}L_{i}\big{(}\phi_{i}(\theta),\mathcal{D}^{q}_{i}\big{)}+\lambda D_{h}(\theta,\theta_{p}),

where œïi‚Äã(Œ∏)=Œ∏‚àíŒ±‚Äã‚àáLi‚Äã(Œ∏,ùíüis)subscriptitalic-œïùëñùúÉùúÉùõº‚àásubscriptùêøùëñùúÉsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñ\phi_{i}(\theta)=\theta-\alpha\nabla L_{i}(\theta,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}). Next, we characterize the convergence and communication complexity of the proposed algorithm for finding a first-order stationary point of function F‚Äã(Œ∏)ùêπùúÉF(\theta). Formally, the definition of an œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-approximate first-order stationary point is given as follows.

Definition 0 (œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP).

A solution Œ∏‚àà‚ÑùnùúÉsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta\in\mathbb{R}^{n} is called an œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-approximate first-order stationary point (œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP) of (2), if ‚Äñ‚àáF‚Äã(Œ∏)‚Äñ‚â§œµ,for‚Äãœµ>0formulae-sequencenorm‚àáùêπùúÉitalic-œµforitalic-œµ0\|\nabla F(\theta)\|\leq\epsilon,~{}\text{for}~{}\epsilon>0.

The above definition implies that if a solution Œ∏ùúÉ\theta obtained by an algorithm is a œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP, then the gradient norm of the objective function is bounded above by œµitalic-œµ\epsilon.

Note that the first-order estimator of Hessian introduced in the subproblem (13) inevitably complicates the convergence analysis of ADMM-FedMeta, making the existing analysis methods of ADMM (Barber and Sidky, 2020) not suitable here. To establish the convergence of ADMM-FedMeta, we impose the following standard assumptions in the literature.

Assumption 1.

F‚Äã(Œ∏)ùêπùúÉF(\theta) is lower-bounded, i.e., F‚Äã(Œ∏)>‚àí‚àûùêπùúÉF(\theta)>-\infty, for all Œ∏‚àà‚ÑùnùúÉsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}.

Assumption 2 (Smoothness and Bounded Gradient).

For each i‚àà‚Ñê‚à™{m}ùëñ‚Ñêùëöi\in\mathcal{I}\cup\{m\}, any ùíüissubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñ\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}, and Œ∏p‚àà‚ÑùnsubscriptùúÉùëùsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta_{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, both Li‚Äã(‚ãÖ,ùíüis)subscriptùêøùëñ‚ãÖsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñL_{i}(\cdot,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}) and Dh‚Äã(‚ãÖ,Œ∏p)subscriptùê∑‚Ñé‚ãÖsubscriptùúÉùëùD_{h}(\cdot,\theta_{p}) are twice continuously differentiable and smooth, i.e., for any x,y‚àà‚Ñùnùë•ùë¶superscript‚Ñùùëõx,y\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, there exist constants Œºi>0subscriptùúáùëñ0\mu_{i}>0 and Œºr>0subscriptùúáùëü0\mu_{r}>0 such that:

(17) ‚Äñ‚àáLi‚Äã(x,ùíüis)‚àí‚àáLi‚Äã(y,ùíüis)‚Äñ‚â§Œºi‚Äã‚Äñx‚àíy‚Äñ,norm‚àásubscriptùêøùëñùë•subscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñ‚àásubscriptùêøùëñùë¶subscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñsubscriptùúáùëñnormùë•ùë¶\displaystyle\|\nabla L_{i}(x,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i})-\nabla L_{i}(y,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i})\|\leq\mu_{i}\|x-y\|,
(18) ‚Äñ‚àáxDh‚Äã(x,Œ∏p)‚àí‚àáyDh‚Äã(y,Œ∏p)‚Äñ‚â§Œºr‚Äã‚Äñx‚àíy‚Äñ.normsubscript‚àáùë•subscriptùê∑‚Ñéùë•subscriptùúÉùëùsubscript‚àáùë¶subscriptùê∑‚Ñéùë¶subscriptùúÉùëùsubscriptùúáùëünormùë•ùë¶\displaystyle\|\nabla_{x}D_{h}(x,\theta_{p})-\nabla_{y}D_{h}(y,\theta_{p})\|\leq\mu_{r}\|x-y\|.

Besides, the gradient norms of Li‚Äã(‚ãÖ,ùíüis)subscriptùêøùëñ‚ãÖsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñL_{i}(\cdot,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}) is bounded by a positive constant Œ≤i>0subscriptùõΩùëñ0\beta_{i}>0, i.e., for any x‚àà‚Ñùnùë•superscript‚Ñùùëõx\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, the following holds:

(19) ‚Äñ‚àáLi‚Äã(x,ùíüis)‚Äñ‚â§Œ≤i.norm‚àásubscriptùêøùëñùë•subscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñsubscriptùõΩùëñ\displaystyle\|\nabla L_{i}(x,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i})\|\leq\beta_{i}.
Assumption 3 (Lipschitz Continuous Hessian).

For any i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I} and any ùíüissubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñ\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}, the Hessian of Li‚Äã(‚ãÖ,ùíüis)subscriptùêøùëñ‚ãÖsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñL_{i}(\cdot,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}) is Œ∂isubscriptùúÅùëñ\zeta_{i}-Lipschitz continuous, i.e., for any x,y‚àà‚Ñùnùë•ùë¶superscript‚Ñùùëõx,y\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, we have:

(20) ‚Äñ‚àá2Li‚Äã(x,ùíüis)‚àí‚àá2Li‚Äã(y,ùíüis)‚Äñ‚â§Œ∂i‚Äã‚Äñx‚àíy‚Äñ.normsuperscript‚àá2subscriptùêøùëñùë•subscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñsuperscript‚àá2subscriptùêøùëñùë¶subscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñsubscriptùúÅùëñnormùë•ùë¶\displaystyle\|\nabla^{2}L_{i}(x,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i})-\nabla^{2}L_{i}(y,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i})\|\leq\zeta_{i}\|x-y\|.
Assumption 4 (Bounded Variance).

For any i‚àà‚Ñê‚à™{m}ùëñ‚Ñêùëöi\in\mathcal{I}\cup\{m\} and Œ∏‚àà‚ÑùnùúÉsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, the stochastic gradient ‚àáli‚Äã(Œ∏,(ùê±,ùê≤))‚àásubscriptùëôùëñùúÉùê±ùê≤\nabla l_{i}\big{(}\theta,(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\big{)} and Hessian ‚àá2li‚Äã(Œ∏,(ùê±,ùê≤))superscript‚àá2subscriptùëôùëñùúÉùê±ùê≤\nabla^{2}l_{i}\big{(}\theta,(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\big{)} with respect to data point (ùê±,ùê≤)‚ààùí≥i√óùí¥iùê±ùê≤subscriptùí≥ùëñsubscriptùí¥ùëñ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\in\mathcal{X}_{i}\times\mathcal{Y}_{i} have bounded variances, i.e.,

(21) ùîº(ùê±,ùê≤)‚àºPi‚Äã{‚Äñ‚àáli‚Äã(Œ∏,(ùê±,ùê≤))‚àí‚àáLi‚Äã(Œ∏)‚Äñ2}‚â§(œÉig)2,subscriptùîºsimilar-toùê±ùê≤subscriptùëÉùëñsuperscriptnorm‚àásubscriptùëôùëñùúÉùê±ùê≤‚àásubscriptùêøùëñùúÉ2superscriptsubscriptsuperscriptùúéùëîùëñ2\displaystyle\mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\sim P_{i}}\big{\{}\|\nabla l_{i}\big{(}\theta,(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\big{)}-\nabla L_{i}(\theta)\|^{2}\big{\}}\leq\big{(}\sigma^{g}_{i}\big{)}^{2},
(22) ùîº(ùê±,ùê≤)‚àºPi‚Äã{‚Äñ‚àá2li‚Äã(Œ∏,(ùê±,ùê≤))‚àí‚àá2Li‚Äã(Œ∏)‚Äñ2}‚â§(œÉih)2,subscriptùîºsimilar-toùê±ùê≤subscriptùëÉùëñsuperscriptnormsuperscript‚àá2subscriptùëôùëñùúÉùê±ùê≤superscript‚àá2subscriptùêøùëñùúÉ2superscriptsubscriptsuperscriptùúé‚Ñéùëñ2\displaystyle\mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\sim P_{i}}\big{\{}\|\nabla^{2}l_{i}\big{(}\theta,(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\big{)}-\nabla^{2}L_{i}(\theta)\|^{2}\big{\}}\leq\big{(}\sigma^{h}_{i}\big{)}^{2},

for some positive constants œÉig>0subscriptsuperscriptùúéùëîùëñ0\sigma^{g}_{i}>0 and œÉih>0subscriptsuperscriptùúé‚Ñéùëñ0\sigma^{h}_{i}>0.

Assumptions 1-4 are standard in the state-of-the-art studies on the analysis of federated learning algorithms (Lin et¬†al., 2020; Fallah et¬†al., 2020b; Zhang et¬†al., 2020a). In particular, (19) is critical for analyzing the convergence as it enables characterizing the estimation error of the Hessian. Assumption 3 implies the high-order smoothness of Li‚Äã(‚ãÖ,ùíüis)subscriptùêøùëñ‚ãÖsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñL_{i}(\cdot,\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i}) for dealing with the second-order information in the update steps of Algorithm 1. Furthermore, Assumption 4 provides the upper bounds of the variances of the gradient and Hessian estimations.

To quantify the convergence behavior of ADMM-FedMeta, we first study the properties of the objective function F‚Äã(Œ∏)ùêπùúÉF(\theta). Denote Fi‚Äã(Œ∏)‚âúLi‚Äã(œïi‚Äã(Œ∏),ùíüiq)‚âúsubscriptùêπùëñùúÉsubscriptùêøùëñsubscriptitalic-œïùëñùúÉsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùëûùëñF_{i}(\theta)\triangleq L_{i}\big{(}\phi_{i}(\theta),\mathcal{D}^{q}_{i}\big{)}. Based on Assumptions 2 and 3, we have the following result about the smoothness of FisubscriptùêπùëñF_{i} as in the standard analysis of federated meta-learning approaches.

Lemma 0.

Given Assumptions 2 and 3, for each i‚àà‚Ñê‚à™{m}ùëñ‚Ñêùëöi\in\mathcal{I}\cup\{m\}, FisubscriptùêπùëñF_{i} is proper and ŒΩisubscriptùúàùëñ\nu_{i}-smooth, i.e.,

(23) ‚Äñ‚àáFi‚Äã(x)‚àí‚àáFi‚Äã(y)‚Äñ‚â§ŒΩi‚Äã‚Äñx‚àíy‚Äñ,‚àÄx,y‚àà‚Ñùn,formulae-sequencenorm‚àásubscriptùêπùëñùë•‚àásubscriptùêπùëñùë¶subscriptùúàùëñnormùë•ùë¶for-allùë•ùë¶superscript‚Ñùùëõ\displaystyle\|\nabla F_{i}(x)-\nabla F_{i}(y)\|\leq\nu_{i}\|x-y\|,~{}\forall x,y\in\mathbb{R}^{n},

where ŒΩisubscriptùúàùëñ\nu_{i} is defined as follows:

(24) ŒΩi‚âú(1+Œ±‚ÄãŒºi)‚Äã(1+Œºi)‚ÄãŒºi+Œ±‚ÄãŒ≤i‚ÄãŒ∂i.‚âúsubscriptùúàùëñ1ùõºsubscriptùúáùëñ1subscriptùúáùëñsubscriptùúáùëñùõºsubscriptùõΩùëñsubscriptùúÅùëñ\displaystyle\nu_{i}\triangleq(1+\alpha\mu_{i})(1+\mu_{i})\mu_{i}+\alpha\beta_{i}\zeta_{i}.
Proof.

The proof is standard. The detailed proof is provided in Appendix A of the technical report (Yue et¬†al., 2020). ‚àé

Next, we impose the assumptions on the hyper-parameters.

Assumption 5.

For all i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I}, œÅisubscriptùúåùëñ\rho_{i} is large enough such that:

(25) œÅi2‚àí4‚Äãwi‚ÄãŒΩi>0,subscriptùúåùëñ24subscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùúàùëñ0\displaystyle\frac{\rho_{i}}{2}-4w_{i}\nu_{i}>0,
(26) œÅi2‚àí2‚Äãwi2‚ÄãŒΩi2‚Äã(4‚Äãwi‚ÄãŒΩiœÅi2+1œÅi)‚àíŒª‚ÄãŒºr2‚ÄãI>0,subscriptùúåùëñ22subscriptsuperscriptùë§2ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúà2ùëñ4subscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùúàùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúå2ùëñ1subscriptùúåùëñùúÜsubscriptùúáùëü2ùêº0\displaystyle\frac{\rho_{i}}{2}-2w^{2}_{i}\nu^{2}_{i}\bigg{(}\frac{4w_{i}\nu_{i}}{\rho^{2}_{i}}+\frac{1}{\rho_{i}}\bigg{)}-\frac{\lambda\mu_{r}}{2I}>0,
(27) œÅi‚àí3‚ÄãŒΩi>0,subscriptùúåùëñ3subscriptùúàùëñ0\displaystyle\rho_{i}-3\nu_{i}>0,

where ŒΩisubscriptùúàùëñ\nu_{i} is a smooth scalar defined in (24). Besides, for all i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I}, the additional degree of freedom parameter {Œ¥i,t}subscriptùõøùëñùë°\{\delta_{i,t}\} for the approximation of Hessian-gradient products is chosen to be a monotonically non-increasing positive sequence and satisfies ‚àët=1‚àûŒ¥i,t<‚àûsubscriptsuperscriptùë°1subscriptùõøùëñùë°\sum^{\infty}_{t=1}\delta_{i,t}<\infty.

We impose Assumption 5 on the penalty parameter œÅisubscriptùúåùëñ\rho_{i} and the degree of freedom parameter Œ¥i,tsubscriptùõøùëñùë°\delta_{i,t}. Intuitively, (25)-(27) imply that a large œÅisubscriptùúåùëñ\rho_{i} is required to balance the error caused by the linear approximation and Hessian estimation in (13).

Based on Lemma 2, we are ready to establish the convergence and characterize the communication complexity for Algorithm 1.

Theorem 3 (Convergence and Communication Complexity).

Under Assumptions 1-5, we have the following results based on Algorithm 1:

  1. (i)

    {Œ∏t}superscriptùúÉùë°\{\theta^{t}\} has at least one limit point and each limit point Œ∏‚àósuperscriptùúÉ\theta^{*} is a stationary solution of (2), i.e., ‚Äñ‚àáF‚Äã(Œ∏‚àó)‚Äñ=0norm‚àáùêπsuperscriptùúÉ0\|\nabla F(\theta^{*})\|=0.

  2. (ii)

    Algorithm 1 finds an œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP of Problem (2)-(4) after at most ùí™‚Äã(1/œµ2)ùí™1superscriptitalic-œµ2\mathcal{O}(1/\epsilon^{2}) communication rounds.

Proof.

For part (i), we first characterize the successive difference of the augmented Lagrangian function. Based on that, we next show limt‚Üí‚àû‚ÄñŒ∏it+1‚àíŒ∏it‚Äñ=0subscript‚Üíùë°normsubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°1ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°ùëñ0\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\|\theta^{t+1}_{i}-\theta^{t}_{i}\|=0 and limt‚Üí‚àû‚ÄñŒ∏t+1‚àíŒ∏t‚Äñ=0subscript‚Üíùë°normsuperscriptùúÉùë°1superscriptùúÉùë°0\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\|\theta^{t+1}-\theta^{t}\|=0. Lastly, we bound ‚Äñ‚àáF‚Äã(Œ∏t)‚Äñnorm‚àáùêπsuperscriptùúÉùë°\|\nabla F(\theta^{t})\| via ‚ÄñŒ∏it+1‚àíŒ∏it‚ÄñnormsubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°1ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°ùëñ\|\theta^{t+1}_{i}-\theta^{t}_{i}\| and ‚ÄñŒ∏t+1‚àíŒ∏t‚ÄñnormsuperscriptùúÉùë°1superscriptùúÉùë°\|\theta^{t+1}-\theta^{t}\|. We prove (ii) via dividing the sum of the Lagrangian successive difference into two finite parts. The detailed proof is presented in Appendix F of the technical report (Yue et¬†al., 2020). ‚àé

Theorem 3 indicates that Algorithm 1 always converges to a stationary point of (2). Besides, to find an œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP of Problem (2)-(4), Algorithm 1 requires ùí™‚Äã(1/œµ2)ùí™1superscriptitalic-œµ2\mathcal{O}(1/\epsilon^{2}) communication rounds between edge nodes and the platform. It is worth noting that in contrast to the previous methods (Lin et¬†al., 2020; Fallah et¬†al., 2020b, a), ADMM-FedMeta can converge under mild conditions, i.e., not depending on the similarity assumptions (i.e., Assumption 6) across different edge nodes. This implies that Algorithm 1 can be applied to unbalanced and heterogeneous local datasets, revealing the potential in dealing with the inherent challenges in federated learning.

To characterize the impact of local data samples on the expected performance on the source nodes, we provide the following corollary.

Corollary 0.

Given Assumptions 1-5, the œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP solution Œ∏œµsubscriptùúÉitalic-œµ\theta_{\epsilon} found by Algorithm 1 satisfies that:

ùîº‚Äã{‚Äñ‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚ÄãLi‚Äã(Œ∏œµ‚àíŒ±‚Äã‚àáLi‚Äã(Œ∏œµ))+Œª‚ÄãDh‚Äã(Œ∏œµ,Œ∏p)‚Äñ}ùîºnormsubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùêøùëñsubscriptùúÉitalic-œµùõº‚àásubscriptùêøùëñsubscriptùúÉitalic-œµùúÜsubscriptùê∑‚ÑésubscriptùúÉitalic-œµsubscriptùúÉùëù\displaystyle\mathbb{E}\Big{\{}\Big{\|}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}L_{i}\big{(}\theta_{\epsilon}-\alpha\nabla L_{i}(\theta_{\epsilon})\big{)}+\lambda D_{h}(\theta_{\epsilon},\theta_{p})\Big{\|}\Big{\}}
(28) ‚â§œµ+‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚ÄãœÉig‚Äã(Œ±‚ÄãŒºiDis+1Diq),absentitalic-œµsubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúéùëîùëñùõºsubscriptùúáùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùë†ùëñ1subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùëûùëñ\displaystyle\leq\epsilon+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}\sigma^{g}_{i}\Bigg{(}\frac{\alpha\mu_{i}}{\sqrt{D^{s}_{i}}}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{D^{q}_{i}}}\Bigg{)},

where wi=1/Isubscriptùë§ùëñ1ùêºw_{i}=1/I and Li‚Äã(‚ãÖ)subscriptùêøùëñ‚ãÖL_{i}(\cdot) is the expected loss denoted by:

(29) Li‚Äã(Œ∏)‚âúùîº(ùê±,ùê≤)‚àºPi‚Äã{li‚Äã(Œ∏,(ùê±,ùê≤))}.‚âúsubscriptùêøùëñùúÉsubscriptùîºsimilar-toùê±ùê≤subscriptùëÉùëñsubscriptùëôùëñùúÉùê±ùê≤\displaystyle L_{i}(\theta)\triangleq\mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\sim P_{i}}\big{\{}l_{i}\big{(}\theta,(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\big{)}\big{\}}.
Proof.

The detailed proof is presented in Appendix G of the technical report (Yue et¬†al., 2020). ‚àé

Corollary 4 implies that despite œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP of the deterministic loss (2) can be obtained within ùí™‚Äã(1/œµ2)ùí™1superscriptitalic-œµ2\mathcal{O}(1/\epsilon^{2}) rounds, performance degradation may happen due to small sample size.

4.2. Performance of Rapid Adaptation at Target Node

While the task similarity assumption is not required to guarantee the convergence of Algorithm 1, we impose such an assumption to study the fast adaptation performance at the target node mùëöm.

Assumption 6 (Task Similarity).

There exist positive constants œàig>0subscriptsuperscriptùúìùëîùëñ0\psi^{g}_{i}>0 and œàih>0subscriptsuperscriptùúì‚Ñéùëñ0\psi^{h}_{i}>0 such that for any i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I} and Œ∏‚àà‚ÑùnùúÉsuperscript‚Ñùùëõ\theta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}, the following holds:

(30) ‚Äñ‚àáLm‚Äã(Œ∏)‚àí‚àáLi‚Äã(Œ∏)‚Äñ‚â§œàig,norm‚àásubscriptùêøùëöùúÉ‚àásubscriptùêøùëñùúÉsubscriptsuperscriptùúìùëîùëñ\displaystyle\|\nabla L_{m}(\theta)-\nabla L_{i}(\theta)\|\leq\psi^{g}_{i},
(31) ‚Äñ‚àá2Lm‚Äã(Œ∏)‚àí‚àá2Li‚Äã(Œ∏)‚Äñ‚â§œàih,normsuperscript‚àá2subscriptùêøùëöùúÉsuperscript‚àá2subscriptùêøùëñùúÉsubscriptsuperscriptùúì‚Ñéùëñ\displaystyle\|\nabla^{2}L_{m}(\theta)-\nabla^{2}L_{i}(\theta)\|\leq\psi^{h}_{i},

where Li‚Äã(‚ãÖ)subscriptùêøùëñ‚ãÖL_{i}(\cdot) is defined in (29), and the same applies to Lm‚Äã(‚ãÖ)subscriptùêøùëö‚ãÖL_{m}(\cdot).

Assumption 6 indicates that the variations of the gradients between the loss of source edge nodes and the target edge node are bounded by some constants, which capture the similarity of the tasks corresponding to non-IID data and holds for many practical loss functions (Zhang et¬†al., 2020a), such as logistic regression and hyperbolic tangent functions. In particular, œàigsubscriptsuperscriptùúìùëîùëñ\psi^{g}_{i} and œàihsubscriptsuperscriptùúì‚Ñéùëñ\psi^{h}_{i} can be roughly seen as a distance between data distributions PmsubscriptùëÉùëöP_{m} and PisubscriptùëÉùëñP_{i} (Fallah et¬†al., 2020a).

Next, we present the following result about the performance of rapid adaptation.

Theorem 5 (Fast Adaptation Performance).

Suppose that Assumptions 1-6 hold. For any œµ>0italic-œµ0\epsilon>0, the œµitalic-œµ\epsilon-FOSP solution Œ∏œµsubscriptùúÉitalic-œµ\theta_{\epsilon} obtained by Algorithm 1 satisfies that:

ùîº‚Äã{‚Äñ‚àáFm‚Äã(Œ∏œµ)‚Äñ}‚â§ùîºnorm‚àásubscriptùêπùëösubscriptùúÉitalic-œµabsent\displaystyle\mathbb{E}\big{\{}\|\nabla F_{m}(\theta_{\epsilon})\|\big{\}}\leq œµ+Œ±‚ÄãŒ≤m‚Äã‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚Äãœàih+(Œ±‚ÄãŒº+1)2‚Äã‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚Äãœàigitalic-œµùõºsubscriptùõΩùëösubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúì‚Ñéùëñsuperscriptùõºùúá12subscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúìùëîùëñ\displaystyle\epsilon+\alpha\beta_{m}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}\psi^{h}_{i}+(\alpha\mu+1)^{2}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}\psi^{g}_{i}
+Œ±‚ÄãŒº‚Äã(Œ±‚ÄãŒº+1)‚Äã‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚ÄãœÉig‚Äã(1Dmq+1Diq)ùõºùúáùõºùúá1subscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúéùëîùëñ1subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùëûùëö1subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùëûùëñ\displaystyle+\alpha\mu(\alpha\mu+1)\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}\sigma^{g}_{i}\Bigg{(}\frac{1}{\sqrt{D^{q}_{m}}}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{D^{q}_{i}}}\Bigg{)}
+(Œ±‚ÄãŒº+1)‚Äã‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚ÄãœÉig‚Äã(1Dms+1Dis)ùõºùúá1subscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúéùëîùëñ1subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùë†ùëö1subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùë†ùëñ\displaystyle+(\alpha\mu+1)\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}\sigma^{g}_{i}\Bigg{(}\frac{1}{\sqrt{D^{s}_{m}}}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{D^{s}_{i}}}\Bigg{)}

Theorem 5 sheds light on the performance of fast adaptation with the previous knowledge, which depends on the size of datasets, the variance of stochastic gradient and Hessian, and the similarity between the target node and source nodes. In particular, if Dis=ùí™‚Äã(œµ‚àí2)subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùë†ùëñùí™superscriptitalic-œµ2D^{s}_{i}=\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{-2}) and Diq=ùí™‚Äã(œµ‚àí2)subscriptsuperscriptùê∑ùëûùëñùí™superscriptitalic-œµ2D^{q}_{i}=\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{-2}) for i‚àà‚Ñê‚à™{m}ùëñ‚Ñêùëöi\in\mathcal{I}\cup\{m\}, then an ùí™‚Äã(œµ+‚àëi‚àà‚Ñêwi‚Äã(œàih+œàig))ùí™italic-œµsubscriptùëñ‚Ñêsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúì‚Ñéùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúìùëîùëñ\mathcal{O}\big{(}\epsilon+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{I}}w_{i}(\psi^{h}_{i}+\psi^{g}_{i})\big{)}-FOSP can be obtained at the target node. However, it is clear that the larger the dataset of source nodes dissimilar to the target node is, the worse the rapid adaptation performs. In the next subsection, we will show these issues can be alleviated via regularization with a good prior model.

Based on Theorem 7 and corollary 4, it is clear that by selecting a suitable ŒªùúÜ\lambda, the regularizer enables the meta-model to learn on the current task while maintaining good performance on the previous task. On the other hand, combined with Theorem 5, Theorem 7 also implies that due to the independence of (36) and similarity conditions, a good prior reference model (e.g., with a relatively small ‚Äñ‚àáLm‚Äã(Œ∏p)‚Äñnorm‚àásubscriptùêøùëösubscriptùúÉùëù\|\nabla L_{m}(\theta_{p})\|) can effectively alleviate the significant performance degradation caused by the dissimilarity between the source nodes and the target nodes.

5. Experimental Results

In this section, we evaluate the experimental performance of ADMM-FedMeta on different datasets and models. In particular, our experimental studies are designed to evaluate the performance of the proposed ADMM-FedMeta algorithm in challenging edge learning settings where edge nodes have limited data samples. Specifically, we assume that each source node has only tens of data samples during the training stage and that in the testing phase, each target node has only 10-20 data samples. Clearly, edge learning in these settings is highly nontrivial, particularly for sophisticated datasets (e.g., CIFAR-100).

Datasets and models. We evaluate the performance of ADMM-FedMeta on three widely-used benchmarks, including Fashion-MNIST (Xiao et¬†al., 2017), CIFAR-10 (Krizhevsky et¬†al., 2009), and CIFAR-100 (Krizhevsky et¬†al., 2009). Specifically, the data is distributed among IùêºI edge nodes as follows: 1) Each node has samples from only two random classes (Lin et¬†al., 2020); 2) the number of samples per node follows a discrete uniform distribution, i.e., Di‚àºU‚Äã(a,b)similar-tosubscriptùê∑ùëñùëàùëéùëèD_{i}\sim U(a,b) for i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I}. Here we set a=20ùëé20a=20, b=40ùëè40b=40, I=50ùêº50I=50 for Fashion-MNIST and CIFAR-10, and I=100ùêº100I=100 for CIFAR-100. We randomly select 80% and 20% nodes as the source nodes and the target nodes respectively. For each node, we divide the local dataset into a support set and a query set (i.e., ùíüissubscriptsuperscriptùíüùë†ùëñ\mathcal{D}^{s}_{i} and ùíüiqsubscriptsuperscriptùíüùëûùëñ\mathcal{D}^{q}_{i}), each with 50% of the local data. We set the meta-step stepsize as Œ±=0.01ùõº0.01\alpha=0.01, the penalty parameters œÅ=0.3ùúå0.3\rho=0.3 for Fashion-MNIST, and œÅ=0.7ùúå0.7\rho=0.7 for CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100, where œÅi=œÅsubscriptùúåùëñùúå\rho_{i}=\rho for all i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I}. We set the regularizer as squared ‚Ñì2subscript‚Ñì2\ell_{2}-norm, and the degree of freedom parameter Œ¥i,t=1/(10‚Äãt+100)subscriptùõøùëñùë°110ùë°100\delta_{i,t}=1/(10t+100) with t=1,2,‚Ä¶,100ùë°12‚Ä¶100t=1,2,\dots,100 for i‚àà‚Ñêùëñ‚Ñêi\in\mathcal{I}. For Fashion-MNIST, we use a convolutional neural network (CNN) with max-pooling operation and Exponential Linear Unit (ELU) activation function, which contains two convolutional layers with sizes 32 and 64 followed by a fully connected layer and softmax. The strides are set as 1 for convolution operation and 2 for pooling operation. For CIFAR-10 and CIFAT-100, we use a CNN containing three convolutional layers with sizes 32, 64, and 128, and a CNN containing four convolutional layers with sizes 32, 64, 128, and 256, respectively, while keeping all the other setups the same as that in Fashion-MNIST.

Implementation. We implement the code in TensorFlow Version 1.14 on a server with two Intel¬Æ Xeon¬Æ Golden 5120 CPUs and one Nvidia¬Æ Tesla-V100 32G GPU. Please refer to https://github.com/XinJiang1994/HFmaml for full details.

Baselines. We consider two existing baseline algorithms, i.e., FedAvg (McMahan et¬†al., 2017) and Per-FedAvg (Fallah et¬†al., 2020b) with one or multiple local update steps. For the sake of fair comparison, we test different hyper-parameters of Per-FedAvg from {0.001,0.005,0.01,0.05,0.1}0.0010.0050.010.050.1\{0.001,0.005,0.01,0.05,0.1\} (i.e.,Œ≤ùõΩ\beta in (Fallah et¬†al., 2020b, Algorithm 1)), and select the best for the experiments, i.e., 0.005 for Fashion-MNIST and CIFAR-10, and 0.001 for CIFAR-100.

To demonstrate the impact of the knowledge transfer and the inexact-ADMM based methods respectively, we first remove the regularization term (i.e., letting Œª=0ùúÜ0\lambda=0) and compare the convergence speed and adaptation performance between ADMM-FedMeta and the baselines. Then, we conduct the experiment using a prior model for regularization and show the performance improvement in terms of convergence, adaptation, and forgetting effect.

Performance and computational efficiency. To be fair, we set Œª=0ùúÜ0\lambda=0 to remove the benefit of using the regularization in ADMM-FedMeta. We repeat the experiments 10 times, then show the comparison of the accuracy along with 95% confidence intervals in Table 1. We have the following observations. (1) ADMM-FedMeta substantially outperforms Per-FedAvg and FedAvg, especially on sophisticated datasets. Specifically, ADMM-FedMeta achieves 7.7% over FedAvg and 5.2% over Per-FedAvg on Fashion-MNIST, 31.87% over FedAvg and 10.65% overPer-FedAvg on CIFAR-10, and 27.12% over FedAvg and 28.25% over Per-FedAvg on CIFAR-100. Note that the computation costs of each local update are ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n), ùí™‚Äã(n2)ùí™superscriptùëõ2\mathcal{O}(n^{2}), and ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n) for FedAvg, Per-FedAvg, and ADMM-FedMeta, respectively. This performance improvement clearly indicates that ADMM-FedMeta is more computationally efficient on non-convex loss and heterogeneous datasets with a small number of data samples. (2) It should be noted that the gaps between ADMM-FedMeta and the two baselines on CIFAR-10 are smaller when the number of local updates increases. The underlying rationale is that with more local update steps, the number of the overall iterations in the two baseline algorithms actually increases, thus resulting in a better model. However, a large number of local update steps would lead to high computational cost and may cause failure to convergence (Fallah et¬†al., 2020b, Theorem 4.5).

Convergence speed and hyper-parameter. As shown in Figure 2, ADMM-FedMeta converges significantly faster than the existing methods, often requiring tens of rounds to obtain a high-quality meta-model, which indicates ADMM-FedMeta can achieve a great communication efficiency. Besides, Figure 2 also suggests that despite the sample size is small, edge nodes can obtain a satisfactory model via federated meta-learning with only one-step stochastic gradient descent. Further, we investigate the impact of the hyper-parameter œÅùúå\rho on the convergence of ADMM-FedMeta (we let œÅisubscriptùúåùëñ\rho_{i} be the same across different nodes). It can be seen from Figure 3 that ADMM-FedMeta has a relatively faster convergence speed with a smaller œÅùúå\rho in terms of the training loss. In particular, a small change of œÅùúå\rho does not greatly affect the convergence properties of the algorithm, which implies that ADMM-FedMeta is robust to the hyper-parameters.

Forgetting effect to the previous task. To demonstrate the forgetting effect to the prior task on different algorithms, we pre-train a model Œ∏psubscriptùúÉùëù\theta_{p} with satisfactory performance on the data of the first five classes as a prior task, and then use Œ∏psubscriptùúÉùëù\theta_{p} as the initialization to train the meta-models by different algorithms on the data of the last five classes as a new task. Similarly, over CIFAR-100, we use the first fifty classes and the last fifty classes as the prior and new tasks respectively. After that, We test the adaptation performance of the meta-models on the prior and new tasks to show the forgetting effect. We set Œª=0.5ùúÜ0.5\lambda=0.5 for Fashion-MNIST, Œª=1ùúÜ1\lambda=1 for CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100, and use squared Euclidean distance as the regularizer. As illustrated in Table 2, the existing methods suffer from the catastrophic forgetting on the previous task due to a lack of mechanisms to extract the knowledge from the prior model. Clearly, ADMM-FedMeta can effectively mitigate this issue via a regularization with the prior model, while also maintaining a satisfactory performance on the new task.

Impact of prior knowledge. To quantify the impact of the knowledge transfer on the convergence of model training and the adaptation performance of target nodes, we pre-train a prior model as Œ∏psubscriptùúÉùëù\theta_{p} using images of 3-10 classes on CIFAR-10. Then, we train the meta-model Œ∏ùúÉ\theta on source nodes with images of 1-8 classes and test the accuracy on the target nodes with all 1-10 classes. In this way, the pre-trained model can be considered as containing valuable knowledge of the current task. As shown in Figure 4, with the useful knowledge transferred from the previous task to the edge nodes, faster convergence, and higher adaptation performance are achieved by appropriately selecting the trade-off parameter ŒªùúÜ\lambda. In other words, the regularization with useful knowledge transfer can help get a high-quality meta-model and achieve faster edge learning.

6. Conclusion

In this paper, we presented an inexact-ADMM based federated meta-learning approach for fast and continual edge learning. More specifically, we first proposed a platform-aided federated meta-learning architecture enabling edge nodes to collaboratively learn a meta-model with the knowledge transfer of previous tasks. We cast the federated meta-learning problem as a regularized optimization problem, where the previous knowledge is extracted as regularization. Then, we devised an ADMM based algorithm, namely ADMM-FedMeta, in which the original problem is decomposed into many subproblems which can be solved in parallel across edge nodes and the platform. Further, we developed a variant of the inexact-ADMM method to reduce the computational cost per round to ùí™‚Äã(n)ùí™ùëõ\mathcal{O}(n) via employing linear approximation as well as Hessian estimation. We provided a comprehensive analysis and empirical results to demonstrate the effectiveness and efficiency of ADMM-FedMeta. The advantages of the proposed algorithm are summarized as follows: First, it can decouple the regularizer from edge nodes to the platform, which helps to alleviate the local computational cost while exploiting the resources between local devices and the server effectively. Besides, by inexact-ADMM technique, we further reduce the computational complexity during local update and global aggregation. We show that ADMM-FedMeta can converge under mild conditions, particularly, with weak task similarity assumptions. Lastly, empirical results show that ADMM-FedMeta converges faster than existing benchmark algorithms.

There are a number of interesting questions and directions for future work. First, it is of interest to incorporate the experience replay method and parameter isolation approaches into the ADMM-FedMeta to further mitigate the catastrophic forgetting. Secondly, despite ADMM-FedMeta can be directly applied to reinforcement learning with policy gradient, it may lead to poor sample efficiency. It remains largely open to develop efficient collaborative reinforcement learning for edge learning. Moreover, our experimental results indicate that even without the regularization term, in practice ADMM-FedMeta can still converge faster than the existing gradient-based methods, especially on small sample sizes. It is intriguing to get a more deep understanding of this phenomenon.

Appendix C Proof of Lemma 1

Appendix F Proof of Theorem 3

First, we prove part (i). Next, we show limt‚Üí‚àû‚ÄñŒ∏it+1‚àíŒ∏it‚Äñ=0subscript‚Üíùë°normsubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°1ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°ùëñ0\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\|\theta^{t+1}_{i}-\theta^{t}_{i}\|=0 and limt‚Üí‚àû‚ÄñŒ∏t+1‚àíŒ∏t‚Äñ=0subscript‚Üíùë°normsuperscriptùúÉùë°1superscriptùúÉùë°0\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\|\theta^{t+1}-\theta^{t}\|=0 by two steps.

  1. 1)

    (80) limt‚Üí‚àû‚ÄñŒ∏t+1‚àíŒ∏t‚Äñ=0.subscript‚Üíùë°normsuperscriptùúÉùë°1superscriptùúÉùë°0\displaystyle\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\|\theta^{t+1}-\theta^{t}\|=0.

    By Lemma 1 and (14), we can show that

    (89) limt‚Üí‚àû‚ÄñŒ∏tq+1‚àíŒ∏tq‚Äñ=0.subscript‚Üíùë°normsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùë°ùëû1superscriptùúÉsubscriptùë°ùëû0\displaystyle\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\|\theta^{t_{q}+1}-\theta^{t_{q}}\|=0.

Using the optimality condition of (13) leads to

‚Äñ‚àáŒ∏it+1‚Ñí‚Äã({Œ∏it+1,yit+1},Œ∏t+1)‚Äñnormsubscript‚àásubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°1ùëñ‚ÑísubscriptsuperscriptùúÉùë°1ùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùë¶ùë°1ùëñsuperscriptùúÉùë°1\displaystyle\|\nabla_{\theta^{t+1}_{i}}\mathcal{L}\big{(}\{\theta^{t+1}_{i},y^{t+1}_{i}\},\theta^{t+1}\big{)}\|

thereby completing the proof.

Appendix H Proof of Theorem 5

Appendix I Proof of Lemma 6
